t1047.text: In conclusion, I think the LNP is ready to look at ways to backflip on Climate Change with sensible Carbon pricing without the trash talk on destroying Coal jobs just because there’s not many votes there.

t1048.text: It’s almost a Qld cultural instinct not to bite the hand that feeds (Qlders even in Brisbane will support coal mining, for its royalties and prevent a NQExit) , but may see a Carbon Tax as another avenue of royalty rather than an “energy tax” of 9years ago.

t1049.text: Of how royalties on the back of (then Gold) mining we’re consistently earned in the country, to bank roll the State Government, that spent it near Brisbane infrastructure and pork barelling. This continues to this day with Coal etc.

t1050.text: If the conservative side of Government broaches the subject, country Australians will be reassured that they aren’t just out to destroy mining investments and jobs to buy votes in the cities. There is a long history, from when Qld was first created of Royalties.

t1051.text: In my opinion the LNP should be the ones to implement a Carbon Tax. It would accelerate investment in solar farms, transmission, and despatchable power (peak hydro, battery) that will benefit country Queensland greatly.

t1052.text: Solar farms (construction) is providing useful employment in an otherwise grim recent outlook. Usefully, feed in tariffs have been removed, allowing market elasticity to do its thing, and hopefully that will extend to transmission line investment.

t1053.text: A Carbon Tax would work much better, and there is some evidence that even the short term signal it made, prompted investment in Solar farms over Coal power stations to cover demand surges. Solar farms are very popular in country Queensland.

t1054.text: The green movement’s most popular policies, that of subsidising rooftop solar, was popular mainly because the money went to city dwellers. Replacing metallurgical coal with alternatives also gives more jobs in the cities.

t1055.text: From that point on the Carbon Tax became, in the mind of Conservative country voters, a symbol of the Lefts attempt to destroy jobs and successful exporting economies of scale that appeared to represent a relatively small number of voters.

t1056.text: It was clear to me there was no science behind the choice. I noted it as “the worst and most expensive decision ever made” by any Government I had seen. Tony Abbott echoed that sentiment at the next election campaign.

t1057.text: Not only Coal and mining was in the sights of the “left”. The Carbon Tax was viewed as just a cover to make money from the country, and buy votes in the city with it. Live trade of cattle pause 2011 was a watershed moment for many in the country.

t1058.text: The Carbon Tax was unpopular both in the country and the cities, but in the country, there was a grand suspicion that the whole point of it was to destroy the Coal industry (and smelting etc.) and there was not that many jobs, and they were all *in the country*

t1059.text: Also, just as important, is whether the elasticity of the market is used or abused, which relates to efficient allocation of resources, no matter the goal. Back to the politics of when Labor/greens were last in power. A fantastic Carbon Tax was legislated.

t1060.text: It occurred to me in the vision of coal free reduction of metals, it’s not the type of jobs, whether the technology is technically feasible, whether the change is necessary - It’s about where the money comes from for these jobs, and *where* the jobs are.

t1061.text: There really shouldn’t be an issue - There are just as many jobs, probably more, in heavy industries that replace metallurgical coal mining and metal producing. To look at this deeper, we have to look at country Australia’s experience with the Green/Labour alliance.
